<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="Cila0.1">
      <p>
1. aṉṟutoṭṭup pāṇṭiyaṉāṭu maḻaivaṟaṅkūrntu vaṟumaiyeyti 
veppunōyuṅ kuruvun toṭarak koṟkaiyilirunta veṟṟivēṟceḻiyaṉ
naṅkaikkup poṟkollarāyiravaraikkoṉṟu kaḷavēḷviyāl viḻavoṭucānti ceyya
 nāṭumaliya maḻaipeytu nōyun tuṉpamu nīṅkiyatu.
 </p>
 <p>
2. atukēṭṭuk koṅkiḷaṅ kōcar taṅkaṇāṭṭakattu naṅkaikku viḻavoṭucānticeyya
maḻaitoḻileṉṟum māṟātāyiṟṟu.
</p>
<p>
. 3 . atukēṭṭuk kaṭalcūḻilaṅkaik kayavākuveṉpāṉ naṅkaikku nāṭpalipīṭikai kōṭṭamuṅtuṟuttāṅku
arantaikeṭuttu varantarumivaḷeṉa āṭittiṅka ḷakavaiyiṉāṅkōr pāṭiviḻākkōḷ paṉmuṟai yeṭuppa
maḻaivī ṟṟiruntu vaḷampalaperukip piḻaiyāviḷaiyu ṇāṭāyiṟṟu.
</p>
</p>
<p xml:lang="en">
<l>1. Starting that day, the drought in the Pāṇṭiyaṉ’s land having intensified, reaching [a state of] poverty, resulting in even heatstroke and heatboils,</l>
<l>[the king] Veṟṟivēl Ceḻiyaṉ  who sat in Koṟkai having sacrified for the lady (Kaṇṇaki) a thousand goldsmiths, [and] appeasing [the drought] with this sacrifice, along with a festival - </l>
<l>the lands also becoming more fertile, it rained, [and] the disease and sorrow abated. </l>
<l> 2. Having heard about that [festival], as Koṅkiḷaṅkōcar [also] appeased with a festival for the lady inside his own land, </l>
<l> the work of the rain (to bring prosperity) [since] remained unchanged always. </l>
</p>
